\chapter{Simulation Results}
\label{ch:simulation-results}

\lettrine[lines=2]{T}{his chapter} presents the results from systematic simulation of the RCC agent-based model across eight scenarios: sex-specific baseline (no treatment) conditions and three treatment modalities (ICI, TKI, and combination therapy) stratified by biological sex. The analysis proceeds in two stages. We first present single-seed results to illustrate representative dynamics and identify qualitative patterns in tumor--immune interactions under each treatment condition. We then present a multi-seed empirical study comprising 160 independent simulations (20 seeds per scenario) to characterize stochastic variability and obtain statistically grounded estimates of treatment efficacy. This two-stage approach reflects the inherent stochasticity of agent-based models: individual simulation runs can exhibit atypical trajectories driven by early random events, and robust conclusions require ensemble analysis.

% ======================================================================
\section{Baseline Simulation}
\label{sec:baseline-sim}

The baseline scenarios run the simulation with default parameters and no treatment for both male and female virtual patients.

\textbf{Male patients} showed aggressive tumor progression, reaching 2,034 final tumor cells over 287 simulation steps, with 29 tumor cell kills and mean glucose concentration of 5.042. Growth was driven by three injected mutations, testosterone-mediated immune suppression, and extensive angiogenesis.

\textbf{Female patients} demonstrated significantly different tumor behavior, with only 92 final tumor cells over 299 simulation steps, 15 tumor cell kills, and mean glucose concentration of 3.167. The slower progression reflected lower initial mutational burden (1 vs. 3 mutations) and estrogen-mediated immune response enhancement.

% ======================================================================
\section{Treatment Scenarios}
\label{sec:treatment-scenarios}

Three treatment modalities were evaluated across both sexes, revealing complex interactions between therapy mechanisms and biological sex.

\textbf{ICI Monotherapy}: Achieved survival (0 tumor cells) in both sexes through PD-1/PD-L1 blockade. Male patients required 143 steps with 11 kills (glucose: 2.370), while females achieved faster elimination at 129 steps with 11 kills (glucose: 2.480), potentially reflecting enhanced efficacy in the estrogen-modulated microenvironment.

\textbf{TKI Monotherapy}: Demonstrated efficacy through anti-angiogenic effects. Males achieved survival at 222 steps with 11 kills (glucose: 2.606), while females showed faster response at 113 steps with 11 kills (glucose: 2.370), suggesting enhanced sensitivity to anti-angiogenic therapy in the estrogen-modulated environment.

\textbf{ICI+TKI Combination}: Produced surprising sex-specific differences. Males achieved survival at 162 steps with 11 kills (glucose: 2.562), but females experienced treatment failure with 6 remaining tumor cells after 299 steps and only 10 kills (glucose: 2.984), suggesting complex interactions between TKI anti-angiogenic effects and estrogen-modulated immune responses.

Table~\ref{tab:treatment-outcomes} summarizes the complete results across all six scenarios tested.

\begin{table}[h]
\centering
\caption{Simulation outcomes across all treatment scenarios and biological sex}
\label{tab:treatment-outcomes}
\begin{tabular}{lllrrrl}
\toprule
\textbf{Scenario} & \textbf{Outcome} & \textbf{Final Tumor} & \textbf{Steps} & \textbf{Kills} & \textbf{Mean Glucose} \\
\midrule
Male, No Tx & PROGRESSION & 2034 & 287 & 29 & 5.042 \\
Female, No Tx & PROGRESSION & 92 & 299 & 15 & 3.167 \\
Male, TKI & SURVIVAL & 0 & 222 & 11 & 2.606 \\
Female, TKI & SURVIVAL & 0 & 113 & 11 & 2.370 \\
Male, ICI & SURVIVAL & 0 & 143 & 11 & 2.370 \\
Female, ICI & SURVIVAL & 0 & 129 & 11 & 2.480 \\
Male, ICI+TKI & SURVIVAL & 0 & 162 & 11 & 2.562 \\
Female, ICI+TKI & PROGRESSION & 6 & 299 & 10 & 2.984 \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

