% ======================================================================
\section{Sex-Specific Analysis}
\label{sec:sex-responses}

The model captures significant sex-specific differences through hormone environment, CD8+ T cell dynamics, and initial mutational burden. Male patients showed 22-fold higher progression (2,034 vs. 92 final tumor cells) due to 3 vs. 1 initial mutations, testosterone-mediated immune suppression, and compromised immune efficiency despite higher total kills (29 vs. 15).

\textbf{ICI Response}: Both sexes achieved survival, but females showed slightly faster tumor elimination (129 vs. 143 steps), consistent with PD-1 blockade synergizing with estrogen-enhanced immune function.

\textbf{Combination Therapy Paradox}: The failure of ICI+TKI in females while succeeding in males represents a significant finding, suggesting anti-angiogenic therapy disrupts beneficial estrogen-mediated immune processes.

\begin{clinical}
The multi-seed results showing female ICI+TKI as the most effective treatment (65\% survival) are consistent with emerging clinical observations from the ARON-1 trial and support the rationale for sex-stratified treatment protocols in RCC. These findings suggest that combination therapy may particularly benefit female patients through synergy between checkpoint blockade and estrogen-enhanced immune function.
\end{clinical}

% ======================================================================
\section{Glucose Field Dynamics}
\label{sec:glucose-dynamics}

The glucose concentrations directly correlated with tumor burden: high tumor burden scenarios showed elevated glucose (5.042 for male no treatment with 2034 cells), while survival scenarios maintained low glucose (2.370-2.562 with 0 cells). Larger tumors drive more angiogenesis, increasing glucose injection and creating positive correlation between tumor burden and glucose availability. The glucose gradient guides immune cell chemotaxis, but depletion zones around large tumors impair immune function through metabolic starvation.

% ======================================================================
\section{Parameter Sensitivity Analysis}
\label{sec:sensitivity-analysis}

Glucose tumor consumption rate was tested at four levels (0.5, 1.0, 2.0, 4.0) using male no treatment scenario. Results showed clear tipping point between rates 2.0 (561 final tumor cells) and 4.0 (0 final tumor cells), demonstrating metabolic constraints on tumor growth.

\begin{figure}[htbp]
\centering
\includegraphics[width=0.85\textwidth]{figures/sensitivity_glucose_consumption.pdf}
\caption{Parameter sensitivity analysis of glucose tumor consumption rate. The transition from progression to survival between rates 2.0 and 4.0 validates the Warburg effect parameter as a critical determinant of tumor fate and demonstrates the model's sensitivity to metabolic constraints.}
\label{fig:sensitivity-glucose}
\end{figure}

\begin{keyfinding}
A glucose consumption tipping point exists between rates 2.0 and 4.0: at rate 2.0, tumors progress to 561 cells, while at rate 4.0, tumors are eliminated entirely. This demonstrates that metabolic constraints imposed by the Warburg effect can determine tumor fate independently of immune cell activity.
\end{keyfinding}

% ======================================================================
\section{Statistical Validation: Multi-Seed Empirical Study}
\label{sec:empirical-study}

To address the inherent stochasticity of agent-based models, we conducted a comprehensive multi-seed empirical study comprising 160 independent simulations across all treatment scenarios (20 seeds × 8 scenarios).

Table~\ref{tab:empirical-results} presents the comprehensive statistical summary across all scenarios, revealing substantial variance within each treatment group.

\begin{table}[H]
\centering
\caption{Multi-seed empirical study results (n=20 per scenario, 160 total simulations)}
\label{tab:empirical-results}
\begin{tabular}{lccccc}
\toprule
\textbf{Scenario} & \textbf{n} & \textbf{Survival Rate} & \textbf{Tumor (mean ± SD)} & \textbf{Steps (mean ± SD)} & \textbf{Glucose (mean ± SD)} \\
\midrule
Male, No Tx & 20 & 30\% & 578.4 ± 880.7 & 223.9 ± 87.7 & 3.102 ± 1.042 \\
Female, No Tx & 20 & 55\% & 257.0 ± 629.3 & 193.3 ± 90.5 & 2.727 ± 0.922 \\
Male, TKI & 20 & 55\% & 201.5 ± 596.0 & 208.9 ± 91.8 & 2.777 ± 1.226 \\
Female, TKI & 20 & 45\% & 204.7 ± 601.3 & 215.2 ± 91.6 & 2.737 ± 0.997 \\
Male, ICI & 20 & 45\% & 665.0 ± 920.2 & 199.1 ± 84.5 & 3.149 ± 1.284 \\
Female, ICI & 20 & 60\% & 273.9 ± 655.0 & 193.4 ± 86.3 & 2.808 ± 1.057 \\
Male, ICI+TKI & 20 & 55\% & 303.5 ± 716.2 & 191.6 ± 86.6 & 2.849 ± 1.280 \\
Female, ICI+TKI & 20 & 65\% & 202.9 ± 604.5 & 207.9 ± 81.1 & 2.812 ± 1.142 \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

The multi-seed results revealed critical discrepancies with single-seed outcomes. The single-seed simulation showed female ICI+TKI treatment resulting in PROGRESSION, but 20-seed analysis demonstrates this is actually the best treatment scenario overall, achieving 65\% survival. The combination therapy shows sex-specific synergy patterns, with females achieving optimal response to dual targeting while males show equivalent performance to TKI monotherapy.

\begin{keyfinding}
The single-seed simulation showed female ICI+TKI resulting in PROGRESSION, but the 20-seed ensemble reveals this is actually the best treatment scenario overall at 65\% survival. This highlights a fundamental property of stochastic ABMs: individual simulation runs can exhibit atypical trajectories driven by early random events, and robust conclusions require ensemble analysis.
\end{keyfinding}

To quantify sex differences, Mann-Whitney U tests comparing male versus female final tumor burden showed: No Treatment ($U=253$, $p=0.1393$, $r=0.265$), TKI ($U=174$, $p=0.4606$, $r=0.130$), ICI ($U=242$, $p=0.2304$, $r=0.210$), ICI+TKI ($U=225$, $p=0.4542$, $r=0.125$), where $r$ denotes the rank-biserial correlation as an effect size measure. None achieved statistical significance at $\alpha = 0.05$. The effect sizes range from small ($r < 0.2$) to small-to-medium ($r \approx 0.27$), with the No Treatment comparison showing the largest effect. The limited sample size ($n = 20$ per group) constrains statistical power; a post-hoc power analysis suggests that detecting a medium effect ($r = 0.3$) at $\alpha = 0.05$ would require approximately 40 simulations per group. These results should therefore be interpreted as directionally consistent with sex-stratified treatment effects rather than as definitive evidence.

